Key Laboratory of Chemical Additives for China National Light Industry College of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering Shaanxi University of Science and Technology Xi'an 710021 China The development of non-precious metal catalysts in heterogeneous catalytic processes is of great importance to the hydrogenation of quinolines for both theoretical and industrial applications. Herein, an effective non-precious metal catalyst, 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41, was developed to catalyze the hydrogenation of quinolines under the green and mild conditions, which can achieve 97.5% conversion and exceeding 98% selectivity to tetrahydroquinoline in solvent-free at low temperature of 50 °C. Moreover, the acceptable results of the reusability and gram scale-up experiments proved an industrial application potential of the as-prepared catalyst. Meanwhile, in cyclohexane system, 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst can further realize a higher activity of the hydrogenation at a lower temperature of 40 °C, achieving 98.2% conversion and 98% selectivity to tetrahydroquinoline. The existence of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys in Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst was demonstrated by TEM, XRD, XPS, H2-TPD, and Raman spectroscopy. And, Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys can be well dispersed onto MCM-41 molecular sieves. For Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, quinoline molecules can be adsorbed by Fe3+ species on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy through the coordination, while hydrogen molecules can be adsorbed and activated by Ni-Cu alloy. Under the synergism of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys, the highly effective and selective hydrogenation of quinolines was achieved at low temperature and in solvent-free system. The present approach offers a prospective idea for building non-precious metal catalysts to realize the effective hydrogenation of N-heterocyclic compounds under mild conditions. Graphic abstract Image, graphical abstract Keywords FeNiCu/MCM-41 catalyst Synergistic effect Selective hydrogenation Quinolines Low temperature 1 Introduction N-heterocyclic compounds (i.e. 1,2,3,4-tetrahydroquinolines, THQs) constitute ubiquitous subunits of a variety of bio-active substances, which are widely used as precursors in drug synthesis, dye, printing, rubber, and other industries [1,2]. The partial hydrogenation of quinolines, as an important hydrogenation in organic chemistry, is one feasible way to produce THQs, which has attracted extensive attention [3,4]. Compared with catalytic cyclization and Beckmann rearrangement, the direct hydrogenation of quinolines extracted from coal tar wash oil or naphthalene oil to prepare THQs has the advantages of low cost, green, and high atom efficiency [5,6]. However, the hydrogenation of quinolines as aromatic heterocyclic compounds is more difficult compared with that of olefins, and the products are difficult to be controlled [7]. Meanwhile, the reaction is also difficult for a potential poisoning on the metal catalysts due to the highly unsaturated feedstocks [8]. Therefore, the efficient and selective hydrogenation of quinolines to produce THQs remains still challenging in chemical industry. The direct hydrogenation of quinolines has been carried out over noble metal catalysts under a homogeneous condition. In 1982, Fish et al. used Ru-based homogeneous catalyst to catalyze the hydrogenation of aromatic heterocyclic compounds [9]. Since then, a variety of homogeneous metal catalysts have been prepared and used in the hydrogenation of quinolines, such as Ru(η3-methallyl)2(cod)-PhTRAP [10]. Despite the homogeneous catalysts exhibit a high catalytic activity, the separation and recovery still remain challenging. Heterogeneous catalysts mainly involved in precious metals in the hydrogenation of quinolines, such as Au3Pt1@SBA-15 [11], RuCu nanocages and Cu@Ru nanocrystals [12], Pd-supported N/S-codoped carbons [13], and Ru-PAL [14]. However, the use of precious metals limits their application in industrial production due to high cost. Over the last decade, Co3O4/N-Gr/Fe3O4 [15], Ni@SiO2 [16], CoCuOx [17], Co/AlN [18], and other heterogeneous non-precious metal catalysts appeared one after another. However, the reaction often operated at high temperature, which increased the cost and risk in industrial production. Moreover, most of these catalysts need to be applied in solvent (e.g. methanol, ethanol, tetrahydrofuran, etc.). Up to now, few report on the application of solvent-free method in the hydrogenation of quinolines catalyzed by non-precious metal catalysts has been reported [19]. Therefore, it has a great potential to design a new non-precious metal heterogeneous catalyst, which can be applied in solvent-free and insensitive temperature system to achieve an effective hydrogenation of quinolines under mild conditions. The construction of bimetallic and polymetallic composites in non-precious metal catalysts is considered to be a promising strategy in the hydrogenation. The excellent catalytic activity can be obtained due to the d-orbital coordination between various metals. Nickel catalysts are widely used in various hydrogenation reactions and possess a catalytic performance close to precious metals [20,21]. Meanwhile, nickel can easily form alloys with Fe, Cu, Zn, and other metals [17,22,23], which are different from ordinary single metal and multi metal catalysts [24]. Ni-based metal alloys as a single phase exhibit different physical and chemical properties. Specifically, Ni-Cu alloy is found to possess a strong chemical adsorption capacity for hydrogen [25], and Ni-Fe alloy is widely used in the reforming reaction of methane and other organic molecules, which can improve the stability and selectivity of nickel [26]. Therefore, the combination of Ni-Cu and Ni-Fe alloys is expected to acquire a special advantage for the hydrogenation of quinolines. Due to the high specific surface energy of nano alloys, alloy catalysts are more likely to agglomerate, which is not conducive to the continuous progress of catalytic reaction. The defect can be overcome and mitigated by introducing supports with thermal stability. A suitable support can improve the dispersion, chemical stability, and mechanical strength of the active components. In some cases, the support can also change the catalytic performance of the active components through strong metal interaction and charge transfer mechanism. Molecular sieves have been used in various catalytic reactions since the advent, which is largely due to their large specific surface area and rich pore structure [27]. Generally, the alloy catalysts prepared by the impregnation are easily loaded onto molecular sieves [28], which can improve the dispersion of alloy on the surface of catalysts. Especially, the introduction of MCM-41 molecular sieve with regular pore structure into the alloy catalysts can significantly promote the mass transfer and diffusion of reactant molecules [29], and improve the specific surface area to increase the adsorption performance and stabilize low valence metals. Herein, by combining the advantages of Ni-based alloys and MCM-41 molecular sieve, a series of FeNiCu/MCM-41 catalysts were prepared by a simple impregnation method, which can be used to catalyze the hydrogenation of quinolines in solvent-free at low temperature. The FeNiCu/MCM-41 catalysts were characterized and analyzed by various techniques. Based on the results of contrast experiment and catalyst characterization, a possible catalytic mechanism of the optimal FeNiCu/MCM-41 catalyst was proposed for the hydrogenation of quinolines. For the excellent hydrogenation performance, the present approach can be extended to catalyze the dehydrogenation of other N-heterocyclic compounds under mild conditions. 2 Experimental 2.1 Materials Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (99.0%), Fe(NO3)3·9H2O (99.0%), Ni(NO3)2·6H2O (99.0%), and Na2CO3 were purchased by Adamas-Beta. MCM-41 (Si: Al=20: 1) was obtained from Nanjing XFnano. Cyclohexane (99.0%), toluene (99.0%), and quinoline (99.0%) were purchased from Aladdin. H2 (99.99%) and N2 (99.999%) were provided from Xi'an Teda Cryogenic Equipment company. All other materials and chemicals were purchased from the commercial company. 2.2 Catalyst preparation All bimetallic and trimetallic catalysts were obtained by the co-precipitation. For the preparation of Fe4Ni6Cu5 catalyst, Fe(NO3)3·9H2O (0.501 g, 1.24 mmol), Ni(NO3)2·6H2O (0.541 g, 1.86 mmol), Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.347 g, 1.55 mmol) were added to the deionized water (20 mL) and then stirred for 1 h. Next, the solution was slowly dropped to Na2CO3 solution (0.5 M). The precipitate was generated and continuously stirred for 4 h. After that, the precipitate was filtrated and then washed by the deionized water (500 mL). Then, the obtained solid was calcined in air by a muffle furnace with a heating rate of 5 °C/min to 500 °C, and maintained with the constant temperature of 500 °C for 3 h. The sample was further reduced in pure H2 by a tube furnace with the same rate from room temperature to 500 °C, and maintained with the constant temperature of 500 °C for 2 h. Upon the reduction completion, the sample was passivated at room temperature in 1% O2/N2 for 4 h to prevent the over-oxidation. The other bimetallic and trimetallic catalysts were also prepared by the similar method with the corresponding mounts of raw materials. The Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalysts were manufactured by a simple impregnation method. And, the samples with different contents of Fe4Ni6Cu5 were denoted as x% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41. Similarly, for 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, Fe(NO3)3·9H2O (0.501 g, 1.24 mmol), Ni(NO3)2·6H2O (0.541 g, 1.86 mmol), Cu(NO3)2·3H2O (0.347 g, 1.55 mmol) were firstly dissolved in 20 mL of deionized water and then stirred for 1 h. Next, the solution was dropped to a flask containing 200 mg MCM-41 molecular sieve, and simultaneously evaporated on detector-ultraviolet detector. Subsequently, the solid powder is dried in an oven at 100 °C for 12 h to fix the nitrate in the pores of the MCM-41 molecular sieve. After that, the solid was reduced in a tube furnace under pure H2 with a heating rate of 5 °C/min to 500 °C, and maintained with 500 °C for 2 h. After the reduction, to avoid the over-oxidation, the catalyst was further passivated at room temperature in 1% O2/N2 for 4 h. For 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the metal ratio and loading have been analyzed by ICP test, the metal ratio was determined to be 4: 6: 5 and the loading was 55%. 2.3 Catalyst characterization The TEM observations of the samples were performed on an electron microscope (JEM-2100). The XRD patterns were measured using a Rigaku D/max 2500 (Ni filtered Cu-Kα, λ = 0.154 nm). The XPS spectra were obtained on an electron spectrometer (ESCALab 220I-XL, VG Scientific) with Al-Kα radiation (300 W). The N2 adsorption/desorption (Micromeritics ASAP 2460, USA) was carried out to study the specific surface areas, and the Barrett-Joyner-Halenda (BJH) method was used to analyze the pore size distribution. The Raman spectra were measured on a micro-Raman DXRxi spectrometer (Thermo Fisher, USA). The FT-IR was performed on a VECTOR-22 using a KBr pellet technique with a resolution of 2 cm−1 from 400 to 4000 cm−1 and consisted of 32 scans at room temperature. The TGA was carry on TG 209F3, the temperature was linearly raised from 35 °C to 800 °C at a heating rate of 10 °C/min under N2 atmosphere. The H2-temperature-programmed reduction (H2-TPR) tests were carried out on an Autochem II 2920 chemisorption analyzer (Micromeritics, USA), and the experiment details were given in Supplementary Material. 2.4 Catalytic performance tests In a typical reaction, 30 mg of catalyst was added into the Teflon inner container. Then, 1 mmol of quinoline (0.129 g) was carefully added dropwise to the container, which was transferred into a 16 mL of stainless steel autoclave. To remove the air, 1 MPa of H2 was charged to the sealed autoclave for three times. Then, 4 MPa of H2 was charged to the reactor, which was heated to 50 °C. Upon the reaction completion, the autoclave was naturally cooled to room temperature, and then the gas in the reactor slowly emitted. The liquid products were analyzed on a gas chromatograph (GC-9720, Fuli) and GC–MS (6890N-5975, Agilent). 2.5 The experiments of the catalyst reusability and the hot filtration After the reaction completion, the solid-catalyst was filtrated and then washed with cyclohexane and methanol for three times. Next, the catalyst was dried in vacuum and used in the next run. Other operations were the same as mentioned. The hot filtration test was carried out. After the reaction proceeded for 12 h, 2 mL of cyclohexane were added as a solvent to filtrate the catalyst. Then, the reaction mixture was kept under the catalytic conditions for another 12 h. After the reaction, the products were detected by GC. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Characterization of catalysts The TEM images in Fig. 1 a and b indicate that the metal particles are attached to the surface of the MCM-41 molecular sieve with irregular spherical particles. The size distribution of the metal particles is concentrated between 10 and 20 nm (Fig. 1b). The lattice fringe of 0.205 nm belongs to the (111) crystal planes of the face-centered cubic Ni-Cu alloy (Fig. 1c) [30,31]. While, the lattice fringe of 0.178 nm can be attributed the (220) crystal plane of Fe-Ni alloy or Ni-Cu alloy [32,33]. Interestingly, in the magnified HRTEM images of Fig. 1c and d, the lattice fringes of 0.270 and 0.232 nm belonging to the (104) and (111) crystal planes of Fe2O3 and CuO appear in the edge of the metal particle, indicating the formation of the metal oxide layer between metal alloy and MCM-41 molecular sieve. For molecular sieves of MCM-41, the combination of tetradentate Si4+ with oxide metals is much easier than that with metal [34]. Therefore, the metal oxide layer is conducive to the combination of the metal alloy and MCM-41 molecular sieve. Energy Dispersive X-ray elemental (EDX) mapping images show that Si, Al, and O elements are evenly distributed in the support MCM-41. While Fe, Ni, and Cu elements are only distributed in the metal particles on the surface of MCM-41 molecular sieve. It is worth noting that Fe and Cu elements are mainly distributed in the area of the presented nickel, implying that the metal particles may be mainly composed of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys. The N2 adsorption-desorption isotherms in Fig. S1 show that the MCM-41, Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41, and Fe4Ni6Cu5 catalysts exhibit the type IV isotherms, indicating the typical porosity characteristics. For pure MCM-41, the N2 adsorption capacity increases with an increase of relative pressure slowly at low relative pressure of N2. When P/P0 is 0.3∼0.4, the N2 adsorption capacity jumps due to capillary condensation in the mesoporous, indicating that the mesoporous structure exists and the pore size is uniform. Then, with an increase of P/P0, the change of N2 adsorption capacity is very small, indicating that it is close to saturation [35]. When the MCM-41 molecular sieve is loaded with metal alloys, the type of adsorption curves of the catalysts do not change, indicating that the metal loading did not change the pore structure of the MCM-41 molecular sieve. However, the N2 adsorption capacity significantly decreases with an increase of metal loading, ascribing to the loaded metals covered the partial specific surface area of MCM-41 molecular sieve. The specific surface area of the catalysts is positively correlated with the metal loading (Table S1). When the loading from 10 to 65%, the BET surface area of the catalysts decreases continuously, and the BET surface area at 65% loading (403 m2/g) is much smaller compared with that at 10% loading (960 m2/g). Specially, the BET surface area at Fe4Ni6Cu5 is very small (46 m2/g), implying that the alloys may exist a serious agglomeration. 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 with BET surface area of 488 m2/g exhibits the highest catalytic activity, ascribing to the appropriate active alloy loading and BET surface area. To explore the effect of MCM-41 molecular sieve on XRD characteristic peaks of alloys, the XRD patterns of the relevant samples are also studied and shown in Fig. S2. The diffraction peak of MCM-41 molecular sieve is almost difficult to detect. The single metal supported catalysts of Fe/MCM-41, Ni/MCM-41, and Cu/MCM-41 show very clear diffraction peaks of the corresponding metals, which are highly consistent with standard cards (JCPDS 06-0696, 04-0850, and 04-0836). In view that XRD characteristic peaks of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys appear in the same position and intensity (Fig. 2 b), thus the diffraction peak of Fe4Ni6Cu5 and Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 at 43.6, 50.8, and 74.7° can be attributed to the (111), (200), and (220) crystal planes of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys (JCPDS 47-1405 and 47-1406), respectively. For Fe4Ni6Cu5 and 42% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 samples, the characteristic peaks of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys appear splitting peak (Fig. 2a), implying a complex species environment at characteristic crystal planes. Except for three characteristic peaks of alloy, the splitting peaks of Fe4Ni6Cu5 and 42% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalysts at 43.6, 50.8, and 74.7° can be correspond to the (111), (200), and (220) crystal planes of Cu (JCPDS 04-0836), respectively. Additionally, the splitting peak of 42% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst at 43.6 and 65.0° can be corresponded to the (110) and (200) crystal planes of Fe (JCPDS 06-0696), respectively. While 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 displays three stronger diffraction peaks of (111), (200), and (220) crystal plane of alloy, respectively, indicating that the amounts of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys on the surface of 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 are higher compared with that of Fe4Ni6Cu5 and 42% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 samples. 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-4 sample can achieve a higher catalytic activity compared with that of Fe4Ni6Cu5 and 42% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 samples, implying that Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys may be mainly the catalytic active sites. For 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41, except for three clear diffraction peaks of alloy, two small diffraction peaks at 35.5° and 38.7° can also be detected, which can be attributed to (11–1) and (111) crystal planes of CuO (JCPDS 48–1548). HRTEM images display that CuO layer is formed on the surface of alloy nanoparticles (Fig. 1d). Moreover, the formation of CuO layer may be occurred during the passivation of catalyst. While two characteristic peaks of CuO disappear in the used 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst after the reaction (Fig. 2b), indicating that CuO may be reduced by H2 during the reaction. Meanwhile, XPS results also show that the content of CuO is found to decrease in the used 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst after the reaction. The chemical compositions and elemental states of the Fe/MCM-41, Ni/MCM-41, Cu/MCM-41, and Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalysts were investigated by XPS (Fig. 3 ), and the contents of Fe 2p, Ni 2p, and Cu 2p species on the catalyst surfaces were summarized in Table S2. The strong satellite peaks of Fe 2p and Ni 2p species can be observed in XPS spectra (Fig. 3), demonstrating that Fe 2p and Ni 2p species in the as-prepared Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 sample have strong interaction with MCM-41 support [28]. The Fe 2p spectrum of Fe/MCM-41 (Fig. 3a) displays that the binding energies at 707.7 (720.4), 711.1 (723.8), and 713.5 (726.6) eV correspond to Fe0, Fe2+, and Fe3+ 2p3/2 (2p1/2) states [36]. Compared with Fe/MCM-41, the peak positions of Fe0, Fe2+, and Fe3+ in 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 shift to higher binding energy, which attributes to the interaction between Fe, Ni, and Cu components. Similarly, compared with Ni/MCM-41 and Cu/MCM-41, a shift in peak positions to higher bonding energies can also observed at Ni 2p and Cu 2p spectra in 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 (Fig. 3b and c), respectively. This may be because the alloy with a strong binding effect on electrons can lead to a decrease of electron cloud density on the alloy surface, thus resulting the blue shift of electron binding energy of various species on the alloy surface. For Ni 2p spectrum of 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41, the peaks at 853.2, 855.7, and 858.2 eV can be attributed to Ni0, Ni2+, and Ni3+ 2p3/2, whereas those at 871.2, 873.4, and 875.3 eV can assigned be to Ni0, Ni2+, and Ni3+ 2p1/2, respectively. Cu 2p spectrum of 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 is identified to two peaks at 935.3 and 955.0 eV attributed to Cu2+ 2p3/2 and 2p1/2, and two peaks at 933.0 and 952.8 eV assigned to Cu0 2p3/2 and 2p1/2, respectively. The presence of metal various species with positive valence, except for the oxidation of alloy on the catalyst surface, is also a result of strong interaction between metal oxide and MCM-41 support, which may require very high temperature for complete reduction of oxidation-state metal species [37]. The peak areas of Fe0 and Ni0 species in 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 are larger than that in Fe/MCM-41 and Ni/MCM-41, respectively. Especially for Fe species, the ratio of Fe0 species in 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 (24.7%) is much higher than that in Fe/MCM-41 (8.1%) (Table S2), indicating that the formation of alloy is more conducive to the enhancement of Fe0 species on Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 surface. Meanwhile, the increased ratio of Fe0 and Ni0 species after the alloying indicates that the alloying has a stabilizing effect on metal Fe and Ni. Conversely, it is found that the ratio of Cu0 species in 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 surface (70.4%) is lower than that in Cu/MCM-41 surface (79.6%). While the ratio of Cu0 species is the largest on Cu/MCM-41 and 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 surface, which may be related to an easier surface enrichment of Cu [38]. Moreover, the content of Cu species is higher than that of Fe and Ni species on 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 surface due to the surface enrichment of Cu. The enrichment Cu is more easily oxidized than Fe and Ni metal in 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 surface, resulting an increase in the ratio of Cu2+ species. Thus, the surface of 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 exists more dispersed CuO compared with that of Cu/MCM-41, which is consistent with the results of XRD and TEM. Meanwhile, the surface of 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 also exists abundant Fe2+, Fe3+, Ni2+, and Ni3+ species with the form of metal oxides. These metal oxides on 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 surface are mainly distributed in the outer layer of the alloy, suggesting the strong interaction between metal oxides and MCM-41 support, which is conducive to the combination of alloy and MCM-41 molecular sieve. To study the change of chemical states on the catalyst surface after the reaction, XPS test was carried out for the used 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst (Fig. 3). After the reaction, the binding energies of Cu0 and Cu2+ species decrease, while the binding energies of Ni2+ and Ni3+ species slightly increase, which imply that the electron transfer may exist between metal species during the reaction process [39]. Analogizing the electron transfer from Ni to Cu in NiCu/SiO2 bimetallic catalyst for the hydrogenolysis of xylitol [40], the electrons are transferred from Ni to Fe and Cu for the hydrogenation process of quinoline, which is consistent with a decrease of Ni0 species and an increase of Fe0 and Cu0 species (Table S2) in the used 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. Moreover, a significant decrease in the binding energy of Fe3+ species (∼0.1 eV) indicates that the coordination of quinoline-N may be provide electrons to Fe3+ species. He et al. reported that Fe3+ species can catalyze the transfer hydrogenation of quinoline [41], which can further suggest the ability of Fe3+ species to adsorb quinoline molecules by coordination in the hydrogenation of quinoline. Therefore, on the surface of used 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the increased ratio of Fe3+ species may partly ascribe to the oxidation of Fe0 species by quinoline N in the coordination process. To explore the formation mechanism of the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the interaction effects of metal oxides were studied by H2-TPR experiments (Fig. 4 a). The reduction pattern of NiO/MCM-41 reveals the presence of two peaks centered at approximately 273 and 352 °C, ascribing to the reduction of bulk NiO and NiO species with the strong interaction with the support [42]. There are two distinct peaks at 398 and 545 °C in Fe2O3/MCM-41, which can be attributed to the reduction of Fe2O3 to Fe3O4 and Fe3O4 to metal Fe [43]. Generally, the appearance of a single TPR peak indicates that an alloy is formed, and two metal oxides is essentially reduced at the same time. In the bimetallic catalyst, this phenomenon is considered as a common evidence to estimate the formation of alloy [44]. For Fe4Ni6Ox/MCM-41, the H2 consumption is mainly observed at 388 °C due to the reduction of Fe2O3 to Fe3O4 as well as NiO to Ni. The peak at 477 °C can be assigned to the reduction of Fe3O4 to Fe. While the peak at 569 °C is attributed to the reduction of metallic Fe-Ni alloy [45]. The reduction peak of CuO/MCM-41 appears at 263 °C, which can be attributed to the reduction from CuO to Cu [40]. For Ni6Cu5Ox/MCM-41, the reduction peak at 229 °C can be ascribed to the formation of Ni-Cu alloy [30]. The H2-TPR profile of Fe4Ni6Cu5Ox/MCM-41 catalyst displays that three reduction peaks at 231, 353, and 442 °C belong to the reduction of (NiCu)Ox to Ni-Cu alloy, Fe2O3 to Fe3O4, and (FeNi)Ox to Fe-Ni alloy, respectively, further confirming the formation of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys. It is worth noting that the formation of Ni-Cu alloy greatly reduces the reduction temperature of nickel oxide [30]. The adsorption properties of different catalysts for hydrogen were studied by H2-TPD (Fig. 4b). All catalysts appear three absorption peaks at approximately 100, 300, and 670 °C. Among them, the single metal supported catalyst has a weak adsorption capacity for hydrogen, and Ni/MCM-41 catalyst possesses the stronger adsorption performance compared with Cu/MCM-41 and Fe/MCM-41catalyst, implying that the nickel catalyst possesses a relatively strong adsorption performance for hydrogen. Among alloy catalysts, Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst exhibits the strongest adsorption capacity for hydrogen, confirming that the formation of Ni-Cu alloy can further improve the hydrogen adsorption capacity of nickel [46]. Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 also possesses a strong adsorption capacity for hydrogen at low temperature (<500 °C), ascribing to the presence of Ni-Cu alloy in the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. To further confirm the existence of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys in the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the Raman spectra of Fe4Ni6, Ni6Cu5, Fe4Ni6Cu5, and Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 are given in Fig. 4c. When Fe4Ni6Cu5 is loaded on the MCM-41 molecular sieve, all absorption peaks are not visible, ascribing to the shielding effect of MCM-41. Thus, the Raman spectra of Fe4Ni6Cu5 sample are chosen as model to analyze the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. In Fig. 4c, the characteristic spectra of metal oxides are presented due to the oxidation of catalysts under laser irradiation. For Fe4Ni6 catalysts, the peak at 691 cm−1 can be attributed to the vibration modes of A1g, corresponding to the symmetric stretching vibration of Ni-O and Fe-O bonds. While the peak at around 487 cm−1 can be vested in F2g(b) vibrations, which is associated with the asymmetric stretching vibration of Ni-O and Fe-O bonds. Meanwhile, the F2g(c) peak at around 570 cm−1 corresponds to the asymmetric bending vibration of Ni-O and Fe-O bonds. F2g (b) and F2g (c) vibrations are generated by the octahedral coordination of Fe-Ni alloy. The E g vibrations at 332 cm−1 is derived from the symmetric bending of Fe-O and Ni-O bonds. The distinctly small intensity peak at 201 cm−1 can be assigned to the F2g(a) vibrations of M-O bond [47]. For Ni6Cu5 catalyst, the peaks at 283 (Ag) and 500 cm−1 correspond to the monoclinic CuO structure [48] and the first-order longitudinal optical (1LO) [49], respectively. Interestingly, all characteristic peaks of Fe4Ni6 and Ni6Cu5 catalysts can be found to correspond to the Raman spectrum of Fe4Ni6Cu5 catalyst, further confirming that the existence of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys in the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. To further observe the structural information of the catalysts, the relevant samples have been characterized by FT-IR (Fig. S3). In MCM-41, The broad band around 3451 and 1640 cm−1 correspond to the -OH stretching vibrations and the H–O–H bending vibrations of water, respectively, which correlates with the water adsorption property (hydrophilic property) of the catalysts. The strong absorbance at 1088–1227 cm−1 is assigned to the asymmetric stretching vibrations of Si-O-Si [50]. While the absorption band at 805 and 462 cm−1 can be attributed to the symmetric stretching vibrations and the bending vibrations of Si-O-Si bonds [51], respectively. The absorption band at 967 cm−1 can be assigned to the symmetric stretching vibration of Si−OH [52]. The FT-IR spectrum of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst is almost consistent with that of MCM-41. TGA curves of Fig. S4 show that the weight loss at 35–180 °C can correspond to the loss of adsorbed water. After 180 °C, the catalyst maintains good thermal stability. To explain the inexistence of Fe-Cu alloy in Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41, the phase equilibrium of iron-nickel-copper system is analyzed. During the preparation of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, alloys were formed in the reduction process of hydrogen at 500 °C. Based on the phase equilibrium of iron-nickel-copper system [53], the phase diagram of iron-nickel-copper system is given in Fig. S5. From the view of phase equilibrium, the three metals with a metal ratio of 4/6/5 can mainly generate two phases of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys at 500 °C, while Fe-Cu alloy may not be easy to form. 3.2 Catalytic activity for the hydrogenation of quinolines To explore the suitable metal ratio of Fe, Ni, and Cu in the supported catalysts, the catalytic performances of various FeNiCu/MCM-41 catalysts for the hydrogenation of quinoline are evaluated (Table 1 ). For the present catalytic system, in view that the high selectivity is almost always achieved, the focus is mainly concentrated on the catalytic activity. The result of blank experiment indicates that the hydrogenation of quinoline is hardly spontaneous in catalyst-free at 50 °C (entry 1, Table 1). Beside, the low catalytic activities of the supported single metal catalysts are detected. Even in cyclohexane solvent, the conversions are also less than 1% (entries 2–4, Table 1). For the supported bimetallic catalysts (entries 5–7, Table 1), the conversions of Fe4Cu5/MCM-41 and Fe5Ni6/MCM-41 catalysts are less than 1% and 2.1%, respectively, while Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst can exhibit the relatively high conversion (reach to 61.2%) in cyclohexane, ascribing to the excellent adsorption performance of Ni-Cu alloy for hydrogen. However, the conversions of Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst decrease to 24.2% in solvent-free (entry 8, Table 1), indicating that solvent effect has a significant influence on the catalytic activity of the supported bimetallic catalysts. With the introduction of Fe, the catalytic activity of Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst can be significantly improved (entries 9–12, Table 1). Especially, Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst can achieve the highest catalytic activity in cyclohexane at 50 °C, reaching to a conversion of 99.8% (entry 9, Table 1). Even in the solvent-free condition, the conversion decreases only slightly (97.5%) (entry 11, Table 1), thus the solvent-free condition, as a green and economy route, is selected in the hydrogenation of quinolines. To further obtain the suitable trimetallic ratio, the supported trimetallic catalysts of other metal ratios are also evaluated in solvent-free (entries 10–16, Table 1). These catalysts are nowhere near comparable to Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, demonstrating that metal ratio in the supported trimetallic catalyst can significantly affect the catalytic activity. The conversion of Fe4Ni6Cu5 catalyst is less than 1% in the absence of MCM-41 support, which may be due to its weak adsorption capacity for hydrogen due to its low specific surface area (Table S1) and the agglomeration of alloys. Therefore, the high catalytic activity of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 may be ascribed that MCM-4 can increase the metal dispersion, specific surface area, and highly dispersed and stable Cu-Ni and Fe-Ni alloys. To examine the industrial application potential of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the gram-scale experiment is also carried out, and an acceptable 92.5% conversation for quinoline is achieved (entry 17, Table 1). With the introduction of cyclohexane, a high catalytic activity of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 (98.2% conversion) can also be achieved at a lower temperature of 40 °C (entry 18, Table 1). For Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the effect of loading on the catalytic activity was further investigated (Table 2 ). In Table 2, the catalytic activities are very low at low loading of Fe4Ni6Cu5. With an increase of loading, the catalytic activity gradually increases (entries 1–6, Table 2). Especially, when the loading increases from 50 to 58%, the catalytic activity rapidly increases from 30.4 to 97.5% (entries 3–6, Table 2). At a low loading, the amount of alloy phase of the catalyst, as the active site, increases with an increase of loading, resulting in an increase of catalyst activity. At the loading of 58%, the contact area between the two alloys significantly increases with an increase of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys, which is conducive to the synergy between the alloys, resulting a rapid improvement of catalytic activity. However, when the catalyst loading increases to 65%, the catalytic activity decreases to 32.4% (entry 7, Table 2), ascribing to a decrease of specific surface area and metal dispersion for Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. To obtain the optimal reaction conditions, the effects of reaction temperature, H2 pressure, solvent, and reaction time on the catalytic performance for the hydrogenation of quinoline are investigated (Fig. 5 ). For the reaction temperature, the conversion of quinoline is very low below 40 °C (Fig. 5a), indicating that too low temperature may be difficult to adsorb and activate reactants in solvent-free. With an increase of reaction temperature from 40 to 50 °C, the conversion of quinoline increases rapidly from 3.9 to 97.5%. However, no obvious improvement of the catalytic activity is observed with increasing temperature, demonstrating that the elevated reaction temperature has no significant effect after 50 °C. The conversion of quinoline increases with increasing the H2 pressure, and the conversion of quinoline reaches 97.5% at 4 MPa. Interestingly, the reaction temperature can significant impact the screening of solvent. The solvent has a slightly influence on the catalytic performance at 50 °C (Fig. 5c), and the high catalytic activity can also be achieved even in the condition of solvent-free. However, the presence of solvent can significantly enhance on the catalytic activity at 40 °C (Fig. S6), especially for the cyclohexane solvent. Compared with the low conversion of quinoline in solvent-free, the conversion of quinoline reaches 98.2% at 40 °C after the introduction of cyclohexane solvent, which can achieve the high catalytic activity at a lower temperature. These results indicate that the adsorption and activation capacity of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalysts on the reactants may be inadequate at too low temperature, which can be improved by an increase of the mass transfer and diffusion efficiency after the introduction of solvent. Meanwhile, the polarity of solvent is also observed to exist an important effect on catalytic performance (Fig. S6). The order of catalytic activity is non-polar solvents (hexane and cyclohexane) > proton solvents (methanol and ethanol) > dipolar solvents (acetonitrile and THF). The reason may be that the lone pair electrons in the dipolar solvent are easy to coordinate with Fe3+ species on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy, which is not conducive to the adsorption and activation of quinoline molecules on the catalyst surface. For an examination of reaction time (Fig. 5d), the hydrogenation of quinoline goes slowly at 0–12 h, and then the conversion of quinoline rapidly increases, reaching to 97.5% at 24 h, which can be attributed to the existence of a long activation period between the catalyst and substrates. The long activation stage may be the adsorption and activation period of Cu-Ni alloy on hydrogen. Under the optimized conditions, the thermal filtration experiment is tested (Fig. 5e). After the filtration of catalysts, no additional increase of conversion is observed, indicating that the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst continues to be carried out in true heterogeneous ways. To investigate the stability of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, the reusability of catalyst is also investigated for the hydrogenation of quinoline ((Fig. 5f). At the beginning of the three cycles, a slight decrease in the conversion of quinoline is observed, ascribing to the decrease in the dispersion of alloy on MCM-41 surface due to the reduction of Cu2+and Fe2+ species on the surface of catalysts (Table S2). Fortunately, starting with the fourth cycle, the Cu2+and Fe2+ species may be stabilized on the surface of the catalysts. Therefore, the catalysts in the fifth cycle are used without obvious deactivation compared with that in the fourth cycle. Subsequently, various substituted quinolines are examined to investigate the substrate scope of the hydrogenation (Table 3 ). The various corresponding hydrogenated products with high conversion (ranging from 76.0 to 99%) were obtained over Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. Especially, all the quinolines with a methyl group substituted at 2-, 3-, 4-, and 6- positions can achieve the excellent activity and selectivity to give the desired products (enties 1–5, Table 3), demonstrating that the electron-donating group is favorable for the hydrogenation. However, the hydrogenation of 8-methylquinoline needs a relatively high temperature due to the steric hindrance between the N atom of quinoline and methyl group (entry 4, Table 3). In solvents (cyclohexane or methanol) and at a relatively high temperature (70 or 80 °C), the quinolines with electron-withdrawing groups (chloride, bromide, methoxy, and nitro groups) can achieve a high conversion from 86.7 to 97.6% (enties 6–9, Table 3), while 7-nitroquinoline exhibits a low conversion (72.1%) and selectivity (76.0%) to the target product (entry 10, Table 3), indicating that the electron-withdrawing group can inhibit the hydrogenation in varying degrees. Beside, the hydrogenation of isoquinolines can offer a high conversion (96.8%) and selectivity to tetrahydroisoquinolines (98%) under the optimized conditions (entry 11, Table 3). Interestingly, the present protocol can also be extended to the hydrogenation of nitro aromatic compouds into aromatic amines (enties 12–14, Table 3). Meanwhile, the catalytic performance of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 is compared with the previous studies in a similar system (Table S3). Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 can still exhibit the advantages of the catalytic activity, mild condition, and low cost for the hydrogenation of quinolines. 3.3 Catalytic mechanism According to the results of catalytic activation and catalyst characterization, a possible mechanism is proposed for the hydrogenation of quinoline over the Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst (Fig. 6 ). The MCM-41 can increase the dispersion of metal, specific surface area, and the dispersed and stable Cu-Ni and Fe-Ni alloys. Fe3+ species on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy exhibit a strong adsorption capacity for quinoline due to the strong electron delocalization [48,54], and Ni-Cu alloy possesses a strong capacity to adsorb and activate H2 molecules [25]. In the hydrogenation of quinoline, H2 is firstly split and activated over Ni-Cu alloy, and formed the reactive hydrogen species (H*) on the surface of Ni-Cu alloy. Meanwhile, quinoline can be adsorbed by Fe3+ species on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy through the coordination. Then, H* is added with quinoline to form tetrahydroquinoline on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy. The direction of electron transfer is displayed in a blue arrow in Fig. 6. With a transformation of hybrid mode (quinoline N) from SP2 to SP3, tetrahydroquinoline, which is difficult to form coordination covalent bond, is easily dissociated from the reaction system. Therefore, the hydrogenation of quinoline and H2 may be significantly promoted by the synergism of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys on the surface of Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst. 4 Conclusion In summary, a series of bimetallic and trimetallic supported catalysts were prepared and applied for the selective hydrogenation of quinolines to THQs via molecular hydrogen as a clean reducing agent under a mild condition. Among these catalysts, Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41catalyst can achieve 97.5% conversion and 98% selectivity to tetrahydroquinoline at low temperature of 50 °C in solvent-free conditions. Moreover, the industrial application potential of the catalyst was proved by the reusability and gram scale-up experiments. Meanwhile, Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41catalyst can achieve a higher activity for hydrogenation reaction (98.2% conversion) at a lower temperature (40 °C) in cyclohexane system. The presence of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys in Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst was analyzed and verified by TEM, XRD, XPS, H2-TPD, and Raman spectroscopy. The catalytic mechanism of the synergism of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys was proposed to explain the effective catalytic performance. For Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, Fe3+ species on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy can adsorb quinoline molecules through coordination, while Ni-Cu alloy can adsorb and activate hydrogen. The present approach indicates the technical feasibility of non-precious metal catalysts to replace precious metal catalysts, and provides a prospective strategy for the hydrogenation of other N-heterocyclic compounds under mild conditions. coredata.dc:description: The development of non-precious metal catalysts in heterogeneous catalytic processes is of great importance to the hydrogenation of quinolines for both theoretical and industrial applications. Herein, an effective non-precious metal catalyst, 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41, was developed to catalyze the hydrogenation of quinolines under the green and mild conditions, which can achieve 97.5% conversion and exceeding 98% selectivity to tetrahydroquinoline in solvent-free at low temperature of 50 °C. Moreover, the acceptable results of the reusability and gram scale-up experiments proved an industrial application potential of the as-prepared catalyst. Meanwhile, in cyclohexane system, 58% Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst can further realize a higher activity of the hydrogenation at a lower temperature of 40 °C, achieving 98.2% conversion and 98% selectivity to tetrahydroquinoline. The existence of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys in Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst was demonstrated by TEM, XRD, XPS, H2-TPD, and Raman spectroscopy. And, Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys can be well dispersed onto MCM-41 molecular sieves. For Fe4Ni6Cu5/MCM-41 catalyst, quinoline molecules can be adsorbed by Fe3+ species on the surface of Fe-Ni alloy through the coordination, while hydrogen molecules can be adsorbed and activated by Ni-Cu alloy. Under the synergism of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys, the highly effective and selective hydrogenation of quinolines was achieved at low temperature and in solvent-free system. The present approach offers a prospective idea for building non-precious metal catalysts to realize the effective hydrogenation of N-heterocyclic compounds under mild conditions.
coredata.dc:title: Efficient and selective hydrogenation of quinolines over FeNiCu/MCM-41 catalyst at low temperature: Synergism of Fe-Ni and Ni-Cu alloys
